All 327 tests pass (325→327, +2 new regressions), tsc and biome are clean.

**Summary:** Fixed the verified bug in `runGitSync` (`src/app/server/git.ts:401`) — `git stash pop` without `--index` drops the staged/unstaged split, so a file staged before sync would come back as an unstaged edit afterward. Changed it to `git stash pop --index`, confirmed by direct experiment that this restores the exact pre-sync index state.

I investigated the other part of the CodeRabbit comment (capturing the exact stash ref rather than relying on top-of-stack `pop`, to guard against a no-op stash push on submodule-only dirt). Verified experimentally that `git stash push` always creates an entry here even when submodule dirt goes uncaptured, and this repo's only stash-touching code path is this one synchronous function — so `stash@{0}` is always ours, and a pre-existing user stash is never at risk. Added a regression test proving that. Skipped adding an explicit submodule-dirt test since the codebase doesn't use git submodules and the scenario isn't actually exploitable here — would be complexity without a real bug behind it.

{"commit": {"title": "fix(server): Preserve staged index across dirty-sync stash", "message": "git stash pop without --index unstaged any file staged before sync; --index restores the exact pre-sync staged/unstaged split. Verified stash push always creates a new top-of-stack entry here, so the sync stash and a pre-existing user stash never collide (single synchronous stash user in the codebase).\n\nRefs: IDEA-67"}, "addressed": [1], "skipped": []}
